  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law explicitly prohibits money laundering in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by concealing its true source. It is a serious criminal offense because it enables the continued operation of illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism financing.\n\n### Key Legal Frameworks:\n1. **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act require financial institutions to monitor and report suspicious activities. The **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)** specifically criminalizes money laundering.\n   \n2. **International**: The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CTF) measures, which many countries adopt.\n\n3. **European Union**: The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs) that member states must implement into their national laws.\n\n4. **Other Countries**: Most countries have their own laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often aligned with FATF recommendations.\n\n### Penalties:\n- **Criminal Charges**: Money laundering can result in severe penalties, including imprisonment, fines, and asset forfeiture.\n- **Civil Consequences**: Individuals and businesses involved in money laundering may face civil penalties, reputational damage, and loss of business licenses.\n\n### Compliance Requirements:\nFinancial institutions, businesses, and certain professionals (e.g., lawyers, accountants) are required to implement AML compliance programs, conduct customer due diligence (CDD), and report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally prohibited, and robust legal frameworks exist to detect, prevent, and punish this crime.",
